\begin{abstract}
Spam is genuinely infuriating---not just because it clogs inboxes, but because a single phishing email can compromise an entire organisation. Nearly half of all email traffic today is unsolicited bulk mail, costing businesses billions yearly, and the filters most people rely on have a significant blind spot: they analyse text in isolation, completely ignoring the context of the mail client the user is actually sitting in front of. This paper describes Smart Spam Detector, a classification system built around three fused signals rather than a single model. We combined a Multinomial Naive Bayes classifier with a deterministic trigger-word scanner and live Gmail UI signals, then shipped the whole thing as a Manifest V3 Chrome extension that injects a result overlay directly into Gmail's Document Object Model. To keep the backend small enough for cheap free-tier hosting, we dropped heavy NLP libraries entirely and wrote a lightweight regex preprocessor instead, using TF-IDF features capped at 5{,}000 dimensions. Training on a merged corpus of 10{,}864 messages drawn from the UCI SMS Spam Collection and a labelled subset of the Enron Email Corpus, an 80--20 split gave us 96.68\% accuracy, 97\% precision, and 96\% recall. What mattered more to us than that headline number, though, was cutting false negatives---the missed spam that actually reaches users. Our hybrid scoring engine overrides weak model predictions whenever trigger-word density crosses calibrated thresholds or Gmail's own UI signals a warning, reducing false negatives by 70.4\% in targeted testing. The Flask backend responds in single-digit milliseconds, the extension handles Gmail's obfuscated SPA layout through four redundant DOM extraction strategies, and the whole system stays light enough to run indefinitely on a free hosting tier.
\end{abstract}

